          "body": "Hebrews 11:32 names Jephthah alongside Gideon, Barak, Samson, David, Samuel, and the prophets as examples of faith. This canonical placement does not require that every act of Judges 11 was righteous — the Hebrews list also includes Samson and Gideon, whose moral records are complex. The faith praised in Hebrews 11 is faith that trusted God's promises in the face of impossible odds. Jephthah's faith in YHWH as the true Judge and Giver of land, his appeal to YHWH to arbitrate (11:27), and his willingness to fight at YHWH's empowering (11:29) all qualify for the author of Hebrews' category. Douglas Moo and F. F. Bruce note that Hebrews 11 celebrates the *direction* of faith, not the perfection of the believer's moral record. The chapter stands as a warning and a promise simultaneously: warning, that the same mouth that proclaims YHWH as Judge can make a vow that destroys one's household; promise, that God's Spirit moves even through leaders whose faith is tangled with anxiety, manipulation, and rash speech. Jephthah is not a model to imitate in every particular. He is a witness that YHWH delivers Israel through deeply flawed instruments — a witness that the book of Judges repeats with every judge it narrates."
